  <section class="fyre-comment-body">
    <div class="fyre-comment">
      <p><p><a vocab="http://schema.org" typeof="Person" rel="nofollow" resource="acct:5160916cbb9fd922040022c2@time.fyre.co" data-lf-handle="" data-lf-provider="livefyre" property="url" target="_blank" class="fyre-mention fyre-mention-livefyre">@<span property="name">MarkHolland</span></a><span> <a vocab="http://schema.org" typeof="Person" rel="nofollow" resource="acct:50c1297abb9fd90167000e6f@time.fyre.co" data-lf-handle="" data-lf-provider="livefyre" property="url" target="_blank" class="fyre-mention fyre-mention-livefyre">@<span property="name">VictorColeiro</span></a></span>Because he's wrong. Without critical mass nothing will replace Bitcoin. I could create a new social network to compete with Facebook, but no-one will use it because their friends are not using it. The only way I could beat Facebook is by somehow offering a better user experience. So far none of the competing digital currencies offer any advantage over Bitcoin. </p></p>
